6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both Vertex and Orderly Network calculate funding rates hourly based on the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices. Vertex operates its own orderbook directly on Arbitrum with cross-margin calculations, while Orderly provides shared liquidity infrastructure across multiple frontend DEXs. Vertex's hybrid architecture with off-chain sequencer enables faster rate updates and tighter spreads. Orderly's multi-chain design allows for arbitrage opportunities across different networks but may create latency in rate synchronization. Both platforms use similar funding rate caps and smoothing mechanisms to prevent extreme payments."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Vertex typically offers better opportunities due to lower taker fees (0.03% vs 0.05%) and faster execution through its hybrid sequencer. However, Orderly's multi-chain access may provide unique cross-chain arbitrage possibilities."},{"question":"How do funding rate calculations differ between Vertex and Orderly?","answer":"Both use hourly funding intervals with similar premium-based calculations. Vertex processes rates directly on Arbitrum with cross-margin support, while Orderly coordinates rates across multiple frontend partners and chains."},{"question":"Which platform has more reliable funding rate data?","answer":"Vertex provides more direct rate transparency through its native interface. Orderly's rates depend on individual frontend implementations, which may vary in data presentation and update frequency."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage funding rates between Vertex and Orderly?","answer":"Cross-platform arbitrage is possible but limited by different underlying assets and settlement networks. Vertex operates on Arbitrum while Orderly spans multiple chains, creating potential but complex arbitrage scenarios."}]}]
